May 25 2009 	Good for the price	The Stratosphere is among the cheapest to stay in while visiting Las Vegas - but, as the old saying goes, you get what you pay for.Probably Stratosphere's biggest drawback is its' location. It is technically on the strip, but it is on the far northern end, with the closest casino (Sahara) being a couple of blocks away. The area between Sahara and Stratosphere can be a bit dicey at night (winos, panhandlers, hookers, etc.) so if you're older or have young kids with you, you will probably want to avoid walking around.I personally didn't have a problem with any of the local color around the Stratosphere, and found that by using the monorail (accessed at the Sahara) you can quickly and cheaply get to the southern areas of the strip. If you want to go to downtown (Fremont Street) you can catch the Deuce (public bus) at all times of day or night. The ride can be slow, but the bus itself is very safe and, at only $3, quite a bit cheaper than taking a taxi.The standard rooms aren't anything special, but for around $25 a night, I wasn't expecting the Ritz. The beds are very comfortable, and the bathrooms are kept clean. You're not likely to get much of a view, and the selection on the TV is very limited, but I come to Vegas to go out, not sit in a hotel room all day. One thing though - the maitenance department needs to improve. During a five-day stay, during two of them, my room was not cleaned even though I had put out the &quot;please make up the room&quot; placard. Used dishes, laundry, etc, would often sit in the hallway for hours at a time. Also, during an afternoon while I was in my room trying to catch a nap, a cleaning person kept running a vacuum directly outside my door, which clearly had the &quot;do not disturb&quot; placard on it.The rest of the staff was better, though. I didn't have any problems checking in - it only took about 10 minutes from getting in line to getting my room key - and checking out via the TV was a breeze.The bartenders, in particular, were very good here, recommending good places to hit, and being quick to comp drinks if you threw in a few bucks into the poker machines. The main bar, C Bar, has a happy hour where you get unlimited drinks from 4-8 PM for $20, which is a good way to get lubed up on the cheap before heading out for the night.I don't gamble much, so I can't really give too many specifics on the casino section. It is surprisingly small, though, compared to other strip casinos, and I thought the sports book looked kind of dumpy. From talking with other people staying at the Stratosphere, apparently they don't have very high payouts.The shows offered, American Superstars (celebrity impersonators) and Bite (topless vampire-themed show), seemed cheesy even by Vegas standards, so I didn't bother with them. Stratosphere's main attraction is the observation deck, which offers an awesome view of Vegas, and the thrill rides, which are extremely fun if you're not scared of heights.I would also recommend the Top of the World restaurant, but go during lunch unless you want to shell out about $100 per person. There are a few other dining options located in the little shopping mall on the second floor. Most of them are fairly nondescript, but a good way to get some good cheap eats - especially the Mexican place, where you can get a big burrito and a beer for around $8.Overall, Stratosphere isn't the best casino/hotel on the strip, but for the price, it's perfectly acceptable. It's a nice place to sleep, shower, and grab a quick bite and couple of drinks before heading out to get the &quot;real&quot; Vegas experience.	
May 24 2009 	Good value on North Strip clean and human-size hotel	After coming back for the fouth time from Stratosphere, I'd like to say i'm always surprised to read reviews like '' The worse hotel on the strip...'' First, who ever did stay at every strip hotel and rated them. It's definately not a 4 or 5 stars hotel but it's a real bargain on the Strip. No, if you don't plan to visit parks life Hoover dam, or do Canyons tours, you won't alsolutely need a car. Monorail is a few dozen yards away . PLus of this hotel: * not too big, not too small. about 2500 rooms, and a casino floor which is easy to navigate in. * good selection of inexpensive restaurants on site* u can go for free in the tower * large pool with plenty or chair . Lot of space between chairs, which is not the case at Mirage for example. *Fair selection of slots machines *Hotel guests are more on a casual dress code than other expensives options on the strip Cons: *at night, the area between Stratosphere and sahara is a little bit scary . The should send more police there to monitore drug dealers or other bad stuff like this... *strong cigarette smoke odor , mostly on casino floor*exept dining at the Top, option for dinner are not very fancy ( Buffet, some casual restaurants) * the removed self check-in machines which were very useful when waiting lines are long. Had to wait about 30 minutes ,even with a late evening arrival ( 11h30 PM) *make sure to ask for Premium tower beside regency Tower as their rooms are nicer and ask for superior floors Overall, it's a good base to explore Strip, visit some attractions nearby and you still have money to play in Casino or see shows .	
