Mar 30 2009 	Avoid this disaster of hotel.	Dont be tempted to save a couple dollars on the price of your room by staying at the Stratosphere  youll pay for it in the end. I am a traveler with experience staying up and down the strip and found myself at the Stratosphere in March 2009 for a family wedding. Prior to arriving the prices on the website looked reasonable and the room photos appeared stylish and inviting. But the pushy yet confused reception I received when booking my room by phone should have been the tip-off that something was not right.The average room  while clean enough  was well short on dcor, space, and for most of my relatives, a view of anything other than a wall or dumpster. My bedroom shared a wall with an elevator that made it sound as though I was sleeping next to a train. I was not warned of this prior to checking in, and the staff didnt seem to think it was a big deal.The staff at the Stratosphere is the least helpful, friendly and knowledgeable you will find anywhere, never mind in comparison to high standards Ive experience elsewhere throughout Las Vegas. The uninterested room service staff finally provided two wine glasses after numerous requests  for a fee of $6. The staff in the tower complained about management throughout my ride up and down. Apparently the Stratosphere is not a great place to work.The casino itself is average and in typical Las Vegas style is impossible to ignore. This would not be an issue, if security staff stopped me no less than two times walking from the reception area through to the elevators because I was carrying my toddler (there is no way to get to your room without crossing the gaming floor).Because the Stratosphere is slightly off strip, you may be willing to sacrifice proximity to the downtown to save a couple bucks. Dont. Any cab ride to the heart of the strip or the airport is at least $20. So unless you plan on staying in the hotel your whole trip (trust me, you wont) this adds another layer of expense.Perhaps the worst aspect of the Stratosphere was its second rate selection of overpriced restaurants. I could go into detail about the lack of selection and the clichd menu options that are priced the same as far superior venues up the strip, but hopefully youre convinced the Stratosphere should be avoided by now.There isnt much this hotel gets right. Even its free fitness facility  a plus in todays pay-as-you-go market  shares a wall with a pungent McDonalds restaurant. There are no indoor pools  meaning any swim off summer heat is out of the question.Whether due to the economy or the competition between the numerous hotels that dot the Las Vegas strip, the quality of accommodations, restaurants and customer service in Vegas are far too competitive for you to tolerate the Stratosphere. Thankfully this awful experience is one thing that went on in Vegas and will stay in Vegas.	
